==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ore
<hw>Ore</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>⟦amac⟧r</ets>.]</ety> <def>Honor; grace; favor; mercy; clemency;
happy augury.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ore</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ore
<hw>Ore</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>⟦omac⟧ra</ets>; cf.
<ets>⟦amac⟧r</ets> brass, bronze, akin to OHG. <ets>⟦emac⟧r</ets>, G.
<ets>ehern</ets> brazen, Icel. <ets>eir</ets> brass, Goth.
<ets>ais</ets>, L. <ets>aes</ets>, Skr. <ets>ayas</ets> iron. ⟦root⟧210.
Cf. <er>Ora</er>, <er>Era</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The native form of a metal, whether free and
uncombined, as gold, copper, etc., or combined, as iron, lead, etc.
Usually the ores contain the metals combined with oxygen, sulphur,
arsenic, etc. (called <xex>mineralizers</xex>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A native metal or its compound
with the rock in which it occurs, after it has been picked over to throw
out what is worthless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Metal; <as>as, the liquid <ex>ore</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ore hearth</b></col>, <cd>a low furnace in which rich
lead ore is reduced; -- also called <altname>Scotch
hearth</altname>.</cd> <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oread</ent>⟦br⟧
